Please give this a distinct name from the other implementation of CPU sensor.
I will update the class name to AmpereCPUSensor
Should probably only have one cpu service enabled by default. Leave this disabled by default?
I agree. I will set amperecpu is disabled by default.

No, please leave it enabled.  The basic rule in dbus-sensors is that all services are enabled on startup, and only the ones with configurations are used.  The only time we disable things by default when they're in progress, or have bad behaviors that all systems can't tolerate (ie nvme).
Need a precursor patchset to rename this to intel-cpu.

In the dbus-sensors_git.bb,
https://github.com/openbmc/openbmc/blob/master/meta-phosphor/recipes-phosphor/sensors/dbus-sensors_git.bb
The 'cpu' option is used to build cpusensor daemon, and the service name is 'xyz.openbmc_project.cpusensor.service'. Changing these configuration can cause the changing of dbus-sensors_git.bb.
Do we need to do that?

I agree it would be more clear with explicit name like intel-cpu, but strictly speaking, it is not required.
We might want to leave it for backwards compatibility.
We can change the name of source files, but the option name, service file name maybe not.
Yes, we should be changing the recipe as well.
I expected that amperecpusensor run after phosphor-host-state. But it is unnecessary. Just removes the dependence.
No, it is not. I will remove the dependence.
Like we talked about, "cpu" sensor needs to be changed to "intel-cpu" sensor.

I created the patch for Dbus-sensor: https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/dbus-sensors/+/56093
And
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/openbmc/+/56096
Thu, you miss an argument on the Sensor() function. Need to add a 'false' agrument --> std::move(thresholdsIn), sensorConfiguration, objectType, false, false, max,

Elaborate on this, instead of saying it is complicated, mention how it is complicated. 
Also when you say we need a new daemon, justify it too. 
The sensor look very similar to CPUSensor, so I want to know the differences.

The CPUSensor is for Intel CPU, it is using PECI interface to communicate with the host which is also used by Intel. Ampere CPU is difference it is using SCP register map interface. We also support more type of sensors. Creating new daemon is the result of the discussion in the mail list.
Successfully adds CPU sensors for Kudo project.

Yes, it is. Because we support presenceGPIO in this patch:
https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/dbus-sensors/+/45336
Can the dependency be added when it is actually used?
This function create the sensor too. Please rename the function to reflect it.
Why is the flag used here to limit calling createSensorsCallback only once if one sensor has been created? Have potential power on race conditions with entity manager been tested?

Host can be On/Off. The host sensors will only be added at the first time the host is on after BMC boot up. That why we limit calling of createSensorsCallback by only one.
In this patch, I will remove this variable and add it back in next patches.
Only one match is created, no need to use vector

Default device scale factor for its' sensor. In Ampere case it is 1.
I updated it to double for more flexible.
should it be under extern "C" { } to preserve c type conventions ..?
I don't see others code add this include in "C"{}. Is need necessary?
extern "C" {} used to preserve  C code from C++ type conversation i.e preserving  the C-language calling convention present in C header included in .CPP files.

include path and sensor name to help troubleshoot?

I don't see return statement there .
what is the difference between sensorScaleFactor and sensorFactor?
sensorScaleFactor is hwmon scale. It is 1000. The sensorFactor is individual sensor Scale, it is configurable.
Why are we closing and reopening the file every time?
The sysfs can be used by others services but not only ampereCpuSensor.

Can the logic be re-written like calling setupRead again?
You will have to add waitTimer.expires_from_now in setupread, that's all right?
Or abstract out to a different function, like restartRead.
I don't see any reason to do that. This logic is used by many other sensor service in dbus-sensor. It proved the correction of this logic.
nit : better to make this function as const ..?
Is it necessary? I don't see any code in dbus-sensors make this function as const.
I don't see this header used here . You can removed it if unsued .
can you add more details about what signify 3 here ..?
The "device" file is in 1e78a0c0.i2c-bus/i2c-2/2-004f/smpro-hwmon.0.auto/device. That why the match size is 3.
Can we pass by reference? and avoid pointer?
Just coding style. No need to do that.
It is more than a coding style. Reference and smart pointers are much safer. Please do not use raw pointers.

All of pointer in this functions is updated inside the function. That why I use pointer.
If you preference the others code, they don't add findMatchConfig(). All of the finding and matching configuration code is in a long function createSensorsCallback().

I don't see this fixed.  Generally the convention for this is non-const reference, as the reviewer noted.  Otherwise all pointers need to be checked for validity, which adds quite a bit of boilerplate.

This is a very big function doing lot of things. 
As a suggestion, can we split into smaller functions?
If you look at other codes in D-Bus sensors, the functions are even bigger. These functions are split as small as possible.
How are we sure there is a value here?
We are matching the sysfs which created by Ampere driver. So we are sure about that.

Added try catch.
I preference PSUSensor code on this.
Just condition using. Just make sure the condition to be corrected. Both .good() and .bad() are ok.

numSensors too.

query : this should unsigned int if its indicating number of sensors created ..?

Hi,
do we need to change anything else for this?
No, we don't. The patches is fine now.
Still lots of unresolved comments that need resolved.  The precursor patchset to rename the existing CPUsensor files hasn't happened yet.
Remove the header which are already declared in hpp file.
That's not generally how we do that.
I don't think this is needed?
Why is this neccesary?  An ampere cpu is going to produce a set of known sensor types.  This doesn't need to be configurable, right?
It is required. Because Ampere CPUs report temperature, voltage, current of components in CPUs. So unitPath will be difference between sensors,
add_interface() expects one std::string. I'm not sure why we change it to sdbusplus::message::object_path.
FYI, while this has been in review, most of dbus-sensors has moved to io_uring, I suspect you'll want to do the same here.  Let me know if you need help with that.
This can be initialized before line 160.
This can be removed.  operation_aborted is expected on shutdown.
As Ed Tanous said, this is not what we do.
This causes a few cppcheck warnings.  Please correct them.

"cppcheck --enable=all --check-config -I include/ src/AmpereCPU.cpp src/AmpereCPUMain.cpp"
Any comments on this Patch set Ed Tanous?
just minor comment. This change is tested on Mt.Jade platform

Just for your information, the smpro-hwmon driver which is needed for AmpereCPU work was approved in upstream. You can check at https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/next/linux-next.git/commit/drivers/hwmon/smpro-hwmon.c?id=ab477289b90f574c34ca49a210dfe52a078ebf9c

This is mostly an independent issue that should probably be addressed separately, but I feel like we should go through these daemons and decide which ones should really be enabled by default.  Everything-and-the-kitchen-sink by default bloats firmware image sizes and makes our already-glacial boot times even slower; I'm pretty sure zero systems that have ever existed will actually need both intelcpu *and* amperecpu, for example (and I'm guessing most systems probably use less than half of them).  Maybe they should all default to disabled and we should have each platform explicitly opt-in to the specific set it actually wants?

The idea of dbus-sensor and entity-manager is dynamic detection whenever the entity is plugged to the system. That why you see all of the service is enabled by default.
If one system did not support any kind of devices, the disabled configurations are expected to be added.

> The idea of dbus-sensor and entity-manager is dynamic detection whenever the entity is plugged to the system.

Sure, but unless we're actually trying to achieve a single grand unified BMC firmware build that'll somehow Just Work on any supported platform, there's always going to be some amount of static compile-time configuration for the desired target platform(s)...and given that, including every single sensor daemon by default seems like a lot of extra (mostly dead) weight to carry around.  But as I said, it's a pretty tangential topic -- perhaps I'll post a separate RFC patch or something for further discussion outside of this patch...
"perhaps I'll post a separate RFC patch or something for further discussion outside of this patch..." Yes. I agree with this.
While I can sort of see why it ended up this way in this particular case, FWIW `!(x < y)` seems like a slightly awkward way to write `x >= y` to me, personally.
